They inspect and test products to verify conformance to specifications, using precision measuring instruments or circuit testers.
They cut, shape, and form metal parts, using lathes, power saws, snips, power brakes and shears, files, and mallets.
They lay out and mark reference points and dimensions on materials, using measuring instruments and drawing or scribing tools.
They drill, countersink, and ream holes in parts and assemblies for bolts, screws, and other fasteners, using power tools.
They grind, file, and sand parts to finished dimensions.
They record specifications, production operations, and final dimensions of models for use in establishing operating standards and procedures.
They rework or alter component model or parts as required to ensure that products meet standards.
They align, fit, and join parts, using bolts and screws or by welding or gluing.
They consult and confer with engineering personnel to discuss developmental problems and to recommend product modifications.
They assemble mechanical, electrical, and electronic components into models or prototypes, using hand tools, power tools, and fabricating machines.
They devise and construct tools, dies, molds, jigs, and fixtures, or modify existing tools and equipment.
They program computer numerical control (cnc) machines to fabricate model parts.
They use computer-aided design (cad) and computer-aided manufacturing (cam) software or hardware to fabricate model parts.
They wire and solder electrical and electronic connections and components.
They set up and operate machine tools, such as milling machines, lathes, drill presses, and grinders, to machine castings or patterns.
They read and interpret blueprints or drawings of parts to be cast or patterns to be made, compute dimensions, and plan operational sequences.
They verify conformance of patterns or template dimensions to specifications, using measuring instruments such as calipers, scales, and micrometers.
They assemble pattern sections, using hand tools, bolts, screws, rivets, glue, or welding equipment.
They repair and rework templates and patterns.
They clean and finish patterns or templates, using emery cloths, files, scrapers, and power grinders.
They construct platforms, fixtures, and jigs for holding and placing patterns.
They mark identification numbers or symbols onto patterns or templates.
They program computerized numerical control machine tools.
They design and create templates, patterns, or coreboxes according to work orders, sample parts, or mockups.
They lay out and draw or scribe patterns onto material, using compasses, protractors, rulers, scribes, or other instruments.
They select pattern materials such as wood, resin, and fiberglass.
They apply plastic-impregnated fabrics or coats of sealing wax or lacquer to patterns used to produce plastic.
They paint or lacquer patterns.
They create computer models of patterns or parts, using modeling software.
They clean and smooth molds, cores, and core boxes, and repair surface imperfections.
They move and position workpieces, such as mold sections, patterns, and bottom boards, using cranes, or signal others to move workpieces.
They sprinkle or spray parting agents onto patterns and mold sections to facilitate removal of patterns from molds.
They sift and pack sand into mold sections, core boxes, and pattern contours, using hand or pneumatic ramming tools.
They form and assemble slab cores around patterns, and position wire in mold sections to reinforce molds, using hand tools and glue.
They position patterns inside mold sections, and clamp sections together.
They position cores into lower sections of molds, and reassemble molds for pouring.
They tend machines that bond cope and drag together to form completed shell molds.
They cut spouts, runner holes, and sprue holes into molds.
They lift upper mold sections from lower sections, and remove molded patterns.
They pour molten metal into molds, manually or with crane ladles.
They rotate sweep boards around spindles to make symmetrical molds for convex impressions.
They operate ovens or furnaces to bake cores or to melt, skim, and flux metal.
They observe continuous operation of automatic machines to ensure that products meet specifications and to detect jams or malfunctions, making adjustments as necessary.
They measure and visually inspect products for surface and dimension defects to ensure conformance to specifications, using precision measuring instruments.
They set up, operate, or tend metal or plastic molding, casting, or coremaking machines to mold or cast metal or thermoplastic parts or products.
They turn valves and dials of machines to regulate pressure, temperature, and speed and feed rates, and to set cycle times.
They observe meters and gauges to verify and record temperatures, pressures, and press-cycle times.
They read specifications, blueprints, and work orders to determine setups, temperatures, and time settings required to mold, form, or cast plastic materials, as well as to plan production sequences.
They remove parts, such as dies, from machines after production runs are finished.
They connect water hoses to cooling systems of dies, using hand tools.
They smooth and clean inner surfaces of molds, using brushes, scrapers, air hoses, or grinding wheels, and fill imperfections with refractory material.
They perform maintenance work such as cleaning and oiling machines.
They position and secure workpieces on machines, and start feeding mechanisms.
They remove finished or cured products from dies or molds, using hand tools, air hoses, and other equipment, stamping identifying information on products when necessary.
They skim or pour dross, slag, or impurities from molten metal, using ladles, rakes, hoes, spatulas, or spoons.
They trim excess material from parts, using knives, and grind scrap plastic into powder for reuse.
They cool products after processing to prevent distortion.
They install dies onto machines or presses and coat dies with parting agents, according to work order specifications.
They mix and measure compounds, or weigh premixed compounds, and dump them into machine tubs, cavities, or molds.
They spray, smoke, or coat molds with compounds to lubricate or insulate molds, using acetylene torches or sprayers.
They adjust equipment and workpiece holding fixtures, such as mold frames, tubs, and cutting tables, to ensure proper functioning.
They inventory and record quantities of materials and finished products, requisitioning additional supplies as necessary.
They pour or load metal or sand into melting pots, furnaces, molds, or hoppers, using shovels, ladles, or machines.
They unload finished products from conveyor belts, pack them in containers, and place containers in warehouses.
They preheat tools, dies, plastic materials, or patterns, using blowtorches or other equipment.
They operate hoists to position dies or patterns on foundry floors.
They obtain and move specified patterns to work stations, manually or using hoists, and secure patterns to machines, using wrenches.
They repair or replace damaged molds, pipes, belts, chains, or other equipment, using hand tools, hand-powered presses, or jib cranes.
They maintain inventories of materials.
They select coolants and lubricants, and start their flow.
They assemble shell halves, patterns, and foundry flasks, and reinforce core boxes, using glue, clamps, wire, bolts, rams, or machines.
They pull level and toggle latches to fill molds, to regulate tension on sheeting, and to release mold covers.
They select and install blades, tools, or other attachments for each operation.
They shape molds to specified contours, using sand, and trowels and related tools.
They clamp metal and plywood strips around dies or patterns to form molds.
They inspect workpieces for defects, and measure workpieces to determine accuracy of machine operation, using rules, templates, or other measuring instruments.
They observe machine operation to detect workpiece defects or machine malfunctions, adjusting machines as necessary.
They read blueprints or job orders to determine product specifications and tooling instructions and to plan operational sequences.
They set up and operate machines, such as lathes, cutters, shears, borers, millers, grinders, presses, drills, or auxiliary machines, to make metallic and plastic workpieces.
They position, adjust, and secure stock material or workpieces against stops, on arbors, or in chucks, fixtures, or automatic feeding mechanisms, manually or using hoists.
They select, install, and adjust alignment of drills, cutters, dies, guides, and holding devices, using templates, measuring instruments, and hand tools.
They change worn machine accessories, such as cutting tools or brushes, using hand tools.
They make minor electrical and mechanical repairs and adjustments to machines and notify supervisors when major service is required.
They start machines and turn handwheels or valves to engage feeding, cooling, and lubricating mechanisms.
They perform minor machine maintenance, such as oiling or cleaning machines, dies, or workpieces, or adding coolant to machine reservoirs.
They select the proper coolants and lubricants and start their flow.
They remove burrs, sharp edges, rust, or scale from workpieces, using files, hand grinders, wire brushes, or power tools.
They instruct other workers in machine set-up and operation.
They record operational data, such as pressure readings, lengths of strokes, feed rates, or speeds.
They extract or lift jammed pieces from machines, using fingers, wire hooks, or lift bars.
They set machine stops or guides to specified lengths as indicated by scales, rules, or templates.
They move controls or mount gears, cams, or templates in machines to set feed rates and cutting speeds, depths, and angles.
They compute data, such as gear dimensions or machine settings, applying knowledge of shop mathematics.
They align layout marks with dies or blades.
They measure and mark reference points and cutting lines on workpieces, using traced templates, compasses, and rules.
They write programs for computer numerical control (cnc) machines to cut metal and plastic materials.
They study blueprints, sketches, models, or specifications to plan sequences of operations for fabricating tools, dies, or assemblies.
They verify dimensions, alignments, and clearances of finished parts for conformance to specifications, using measuring instruments such as calipers, gauge blocks, micrometers, or dial indicators.
They visualize and compute dimensions, sizes, shapes, and tolerances of assemblies, based on specifications.

They set up and operate conventional or computer numerically controlled machine tools such as lathes, milling machines, or grinders to cut, bore, grind, or otherwise shape parts to prescribed dimensions and finishes.
They file, grind, shim, and adjust different parts to properly fit them together.
They conduct test runs with completed tools or dies to ensure that parts meet specifications, making adjustments as necessary.
They inspect finished dies for smoothness, contour conformity, and defects.
They smooth and polish flat and contoured surfaces of parts or tools, using scrapers, abrasive stones, files, emery cloths, or power grinders.
They lift, position, and secure machined parts on surface plates or worktables, using hoists, vises, v-blocks, or angle plates.
They measure, mark, and scribe metal or plastic stock to lay out machining, using instruments such as protractors, micrometers, scribes, or rulers.
They cut, shape, and trim blanks or blocks to specified lengths or shapes, using power saws, power shears, rules, and hand tools.
They design jigs, fixtures, and templates for use as work aids in the fabrication of parts or products.
They select metals to be used from a range of metals and alloys, based on properties such as hardness or heat tolerance.
They set up and operate drill presses to drill and tap holes in parts for assembly.
They fit and assemble parts to make, repair, or modify dies, jigs, gauges, and tools, using machine tools, hand tools, or welders.
They develop and design new tools and dies, using computer-aided design software.
They set pyrometer controls of heat-treating furnaces and feed or place parts, tools, or assemblies into furnaces to harden.
They weld components in flat, vertical, or overhead positions.
They operate safety equipment and use safe work habits.
They examine workpieces for defects and measure workpieces with straightedges or templates to ensure conformance with specifications.
They recognize, set up, and operate hand and power tools common to the welding trade, such as shielded metal arc and gas metal arc welding equipment.
They weld separately or in combination, using aluminum, stainless steel, cast iron, and other alloys.
They select and install torches, torch tips, filler rods, and flux, according to welding chart specifications or types and thicknesses of metals.
They ignite torches or start power supplies and strike arcs by touching electrodes to metals being welded, completing electrical circuits.
They connect and turn regulator valves to activate and adjust gas flow and pressure so that desired flames are obtained.
They determine required equipment and welding methods, applying knowledge of metallurgy, geometry, and welding techniques.
They monitor the fitting, burning, and welding processes to avoid overheating of parts or warping, shrinking, distortion, or expansion of material.
They mark or tag material with proper job number, piece marks, and other identifying marks as required.
They chip or grind off excess weld, slag, or spatter, using hand scrapers or power chippers, portable grinders, or arc-cutting equipment.

They preheat workpieces prior to welding or bending, using torches or heating furnaces.
They align and clamp workpieces together, using rules, squares, or hand tools, or position items in fixtures, jigs, or vises.
They develop templates and models for welding projects, using mathematical calculations based on blueprint information.
They guide and direct flames or electrodes on or across workpieces to straighten, bend, melt, or build up metal.
They position and secure workpieces, using hoists, cranes, wire, and banding machines or hand tools.
They detect faulty operation of equipment or defective materials and notify supervisors.
They clean or degrease parts, using wire brushes, portable grinders, or chemical baths.
They melt and apply solder along adjoining edges of workpieces to solder joints, using soldering irons, gas torches, or electric-ultrasonic equipment.
They grind, cut, buff, or bend edges of workpieces to be joined to ensure snug fit, using power grinders and hand tools.
They repair products by dismantling, straightening, reshaping, and reassembling parts, using cutting torches, straightening presses, and hand tools.
They check grooves, angles, or gap allowances, using micrometers, calipers, and precision measuring instruments.
They operate metal shaping, straightening, and bending machines, such as brakes and shears.
They set up and use ladders and scaffolding as necessary to complete work.
They hammer out bulges or bends in metal workpieces.
They melt and apply solder to fill holes, indentations, or seams of fabricated metal products, using soldering equipment.
They use fire suppression methods in industrial emergencies.
They analyze engineering drawings, blueprints, specifications, sketches, work orders, and material safety data sheets to plan layout, assembly, and operations.
They set up, operate, or tend welding machines that join or bond components to fabricate metal products or assemblies.
They give directions to other workers regarding machine set-up and use.
They correct problems by adjusting controls or by stopping machines and opening holding devices.
They inspect, measure, or test completed metal workpieces to ensure conformance to specifications, using measuring and testing devices.
They read blueprints, work orders, or production schedules to determine product or job instructions or specifications.
They assemble, align, and clamp workpieces into holding fixtures to bond, heat-treat, or solder fabricated metal components.
They lay out, fit, or connect parts to be bonded, calculating production measurements, as necessary.
They conduct trial runs before welding, soldering, or brazing, and make necessary adjustments to equipment.
They remove completed workpieces or parts from machinery, using hand tools.
They select, position, align, and bolt jigs, holding fixtures, guides, or stops onto machines, using measuring instruments and hand tools.
They prepare metal surfaces or workpieces, using hand-operated equipment, such as grinders, cutters, or drills.
They clean, lubricate, maintain, and adjust equipment to maintain efficient operation, using air hoses, cleaning fluids, and hand tools.
They tend auxiliary equipment used in welding processes.
They transfer components, metal products, or assemblies, using moving equipment.
They mark weld points and positions of components on workpieces, using rules, squares, templates, or scribes.
They turn and press knobs and buttons or enter operating instructions into computers to adjust and start welding machines.
They load or feed workpieces into welding machines to join or bond components.
They record operational information on specified production reports.
They start, monitor, and adjust robotic welding production lines.
They dress electrodes, using tip dressers, files, emery cloths, or dressing wheels.
They observe meters, gauges, or machine operations to ensure that soldering or brazing processes meet specifications.
They select torch tips, alloys, flux, coil, tubing, or wire, according to metal types or thicknesses, data charts, or records.
They compute and record settings for new work, applying knowledge of metal properties, principles of welding, and shop mathematics.
They set dials and timing controls to regulate electrical current, gas flow pressure, heating or cooling cycles, or shut-off.
They devise or build fixtures or jigs used to hold parts in place during welding, brazing, or soldering.
They fill hoppers and position spouts to direct flow of flux or manually brush flux onto seams of workpieces.
They add chemicals or materials to workpieces or machines to facilitate bonding or to cool workpieces.
They anneal finished workpieces to relieve internal stress.
They immerse completed workpieces into water or acid baths to cool and clean components.
They read production schedules and work orders to determine processing sequences, furnace temperatures, and heat cycle requirements for objects to be heat-treated.
They record times that parts are removed from furnaces to document that objects have attained specified temperatures for specified times.
They set up and operate or tend machines, such as furnaces, baths, flame-hardening machines, and electronic induction machines, that harden, anneal, and heat-treat metal.
They remove parts from furnaces after specified times, and air dry or cool parts in water, oil brine, or other baths.
They instruct new workers in machine operation.
They adjust controls to maintain temperatures and heating times, using thermal instruments and charts, dials and gauges of furnaces, and color of stock in furnaces to make setting determinations.
They move controls to light gas burners and to adjust gas and water flow and flame temperature.
They start conveyors and open furnace doors to load stock, or signal crane operators to uncover soaking pits and lower ingots into them.

They determine types and temperatures of baths and quenching media needed to attain specified part hardness, toughness, and ductility, using heat-treating charts and knowledge of methods, equipment, and metals.
They position stock in furnaces, using tongs, chain hoists, or pry bars.
They determine flame temperatures, current frequencies, heating cycles, and induction heating coils needed, based on degree of hardness required and properties of stock to be treated.
They load parts into containers and place containers on conveyors to be inserted into furnaces, or insert parts into furnaces.
They mount workpieces in fixtures, on arbors, or between centers of machines.
They set up and operate die-quenching machines to prevent parts from warping.
They reduce heat when processing is complete to allow parts to cool in furnaces or machinery.
They signal forklift operators to deposit or extract containers of parts into and from furnaces and quenching rinse tanks.
They test parts for hardness, using hardness testing equipment, or by examining and feeling samples.
They examine parts to ensure metal shades and colors conform to specifications, using knowledge of metal heat-treating.
They repair, replace, and maintain furnace equipment as needed, using hand tools.
They heat billets, bars, plates, rods, and other stock to specified temperatures preparatory to forging, rolling, or processing, using oil, gas, or electrical furnaces.
They clean oxides and scales from parts or fittings, using steam sprays or chemical and water baths.
They place completed workpieces on conveyors, using cold rods, tongs, or chain hoists, or signal crane operators to transport them to subsequent stations.
They stamp heat-treatment identification marks on parts, using hammers and punches.
They set and adjust speeds of reels and conveyors for prescribed time cycles to pass parts through continuous furnaces.
They mount fixtures and industrial coils on machines, using hand tools.
They position parts in plastic bags, and seal bags with irons.
They fit and align fabricated parts to be welded or assembled.
They plan and develop layouts from blueprints and templates, applying knowledge of trigonometry, design, effects of heat, and properties of metals.
They lay out and fabricate metal structural parts such as plates, bulkheads, and frames.
They mark curves, lines, holes, dimensions, and welding symbols onto workpieces, using scribes, soapstones, punches, and hand drills.
They compute layout dimensions, and determine and mark reference points on metal stock or workpieces for further processing, such as welding and assembly.
They locate center lines and verify template positions, using measuring instruments such as gauge blocks, height gauges, and dial indicators.
They lift and position workpieces in relation to surface plates, manually or with hoists, and using parallel blocks and angle plates.
They plan locations and sequences of cutting, drilling, bending, rolling, punching, and welding operations, using compasses, protractors, dividers, and rules.
They design and prepare templates of wood, paper, or metal.
They inspect machined parts to verify conformance to specifications.
They brace parts in position within hulls or ships for riveting or welding.
They add dimensional details to blueprints or drawings made by other workers.
They install doors, hatches, brackets, and clips.
They apply pigment to layout surfaces, using paint brushes.
They inspect coated or plated areas for defects, such as air bubbles or uneven coverage.
They immerse workpieces in coating solutions or liquid metal or plastic for specified times.
They set up, operate, or tend plating or coating machines to coat metal or plastic products with chromium, zinc, copper, cadmium, nickel, or other metal to protect or decorate surfaces.
They maintain production records.
They remove objects from solutions at periodic intervals and observe objects to verify conformance to specifications.
They observe gauges to ensure that machines are operating properly, making adjustments or stopping machines when problems occur.
They adjust dials to regulate flow of current and voltage supplied to terminals to control plating processes.
They rinse coated objects in cleansing liquids and dry them with cloths, centrifugal driers, or by tumbling in sawdust-filled barrels.
They examine completed objects to determine thicknesses of metal deposits, or measure thicknesses by using instruments such as micrometers.
They remove excess materials or impurities from objects, using air hoses or grinding machines.
They immerse objects to be coated or plated into cleaning solutions, or spray objects with conductive solutions to prepare them for plating.
They position and feed materials into processing machines, by hand or by using automated equipment.
They test machinery to ensure that it is operating properly.
They operate hoists to place workpieces onto machine feed carriages or spindles.
They adjust controls to set temperatures of coating substances and speeds of machines and equipment.
They position containers to receive parts, and load or unload materials in containers, using dollies or handtrucks.
They perform equipment maintenance, such as cleaning tanks and lubricating moving parts of conveyors.
They clean and maintain equipment, using water hoses and scrapers.
They determine sizes and compositions of objects to be plated, and amounts of electrical current and time required.
They suspend sticks or pieces of plating metal from anodes, or positive terminals, and immerse metal in plating solutions.
They monitor and measure thicknesses of electroplating on component parts to verify conformance to specifications, using micrometers.
They measure or weigh materials, using rulers, calculators, and scales.
They suspend objects, such as parts or molds from cathode rods, or negative terminals, and immerse objects in plating solutions.
They measure, mark, and mask areas to be excluded from plating.
They mix and test solutions, and turn valves to fill tanks with solutions.
They place plated or coated materials on racks and transfer them to ovens to dry for specified periods of time.
They plate small objects, such as nuts or bolts, using motor-driven barrels.
They read production schedules to determine setups of equipment and machines.
They spray coating in specified patterns according to instructions.
They position objects to be plated in frames, or suspend them from positive or negative terminals of power supplies.
They measure and set stops, rolls, brushes, and guides on automatic feeders and conveying equipment or coating machines, using micrometers, rules, and hand tools.
They preheat workpieces in ovens.
They replace worn parts and adjust equipment components, using hand tools.
They attach nozzles, position guns, connect hoses, and thread wire to set up metal-spraying machines.
They clean workpieces, using wire brushes.
They install gears and holding devices on conveyor equipment.
They operate sandblasting equipment to roughen and clean surfaces of workpieces.
They cut metal or other materials, using shears or band saws.
They dress grinding wheels, according to specifications.
They monitor machine operations to determine whether adjustments are necessary, stopping machines when problems occur.
They inspect, feel, and measure workpieces to ensure that surfaces and dimensions meet specifications.
They set up and operate grinding or polishing machines to grind metal workpieces, such as dies, parts, and tools.
They remove finished workpieces from machines and place them in boxes or on racks, setting aside pieces that are defective.
They file or finish surfaces of workpieces, using prescribed hand tools.
They select and mount grinding wheels on machines, according to specifications, using hand tools and applying knowledge of abrasives and grinding procedures.
They perform basic maintenance, such as cleaning and lubricating machine parts.
They remove and replace worn or broken machine parts, using hand tools.
They compute numbers, widths, and angles of cutting tools, micrometers, scales, and gauges, and adjust tools to produce specified cuts.
They study blueprints or layouts of metal workpieces to determine grinding procedures, and to plan machine setups and operational sequences.
They turn valves to direct flow of coolant against cutting wheels and workpieces during grinding.
They inspect dies to detect defects, assess wear, and verify specifications, using micrometers, steel gauge pins, and loupes.
They duplicate workpiece contours, using tracer attachments.
They straighten workpieces and remove dents, using straightening presses and hammers.
They attach workpieces to grinding machines and form specified sections and repair cracks, using welding or brazing equipment.
They place workpieces in electroplating solutions or apply pigments to surfaces of workpieces to highlight ridges and grooves.
They fit parts together in pre-assembly to ensure that dimensions are accurate.
They enter, store, and retrieve information on computer-aided equipment.
They enter, position, and alter text size, using computers, to make up and arrange pages so that printed materials can be produced.
They maintain, adjust, and clean equipment, and perform minor repairs.
They operate and maintain laser plate-making equipment that converts electronic data to plates without the use of film.
They generate prepress proofs in digital or other format to approximate the appearance of the final printed piece.
They proofread and perform quality control of text and images.
They perform "preflight" check of required font, graphic, text and image files to ensure completeness prior to delivery to printer.
They examine photographic images for obvious imperfections prior to plate making.
They operate presses to print proofs of plates, monitoring printing quality to ensure that it is adequate.
They examine unexposed photographic plates to detect flaws or foreign particles prior to printing.
They examine finished plates to detect flaws, verify conformity with master plates, and measure dot sizes and centers, using light boxes and microscopes.
They perform close alignment or registration of double and single flats to sensitized plates prior to exposure to produce composite images.
They inspect developed film for specified results and quality, using magnifying glasses and scopes, forwarding acceptable negatives or positives to other workers or to customers.
They punch holes in light-sensitive plates and insert pins in holes to prepare plates for contact with positive or negative film.
They mount negatives and plates in cameras, set exposure controls, and expose plates to light through negatives to transfer images onto plates.
They operate and maintain a variety of cameras and equipment, such as process, line, halftone, and color separation cameras, enlargers, electronic scanners, and contact equipment.
They perform tests to determine lengths of exposures, by exposing plates, scanning line copy, and comparing exposures to tone range scales.
They mix solutions such as developing solutions and colored coating solutions.
They activate scanners to produce positive or negative films for the black-and-white, cyan, yellow, and magenta separations from each original copy.
They select proper types of plates according to press run lengths.
They analyze originals to evaluate color density, gradation highlights, middle tones, and shadows, using densitometers and knowledge of light and color.
They set scanners to specific color densities, sizes, screen rulings, and exposure adjustments, using scanner keyboards or computers.
They perform minor deletions, additions, or corrections to completed plates, on or off printing presses, using tusche, printing ink, erasers, and needles.
They arrange and mount typeset material and illustrations into paste-ups for printing reproduction, based on artists' or editors' layouts.
They scale copy for reductions and enlargements, using proportion wheels.
They adjust ink fountain flow rates.
They change press plates, blankets, or cylinders, as required.
They clean ink fountains, plates, or printing unit cylinders when press runs are completed.
They clean or oil presses or make minor repairs, using hand tools.
They collect and inspect random samples during print runs to identify any necessary adjustments.
They examine job orders to determine quantities to be printed, stock specifications, colors, or special printing instructions.
They feed paper through press cylinders and adjust feed and tension controls.
They input production job settings into workstation terminals that control automated printing systems.
They load presses with paper and make necessary adjustments, according to paper size.
They monitor automated press operation systems and respond to fault, error, or alert messages.
They obtain or mix inks and fill ink fountains.
They secure printing plates to printing units and adjust tolerances.
They start presses and pull proofs to check for ink coverage and density, alignment, and registration.
They verify that paper and ink meet the specifications for a given job.
They maintain time or production records.
They monitor environmental factors, such as humidity and temperature, that may impact equipment performance and make necessary adjustments.
They monitor inventory levels on a regular basis, ordering or requesting additional supplies, as necessary.
They adjust digital files to alter print elements, such as fonts, graphics, or color separations.
They download or scan files to be printed, using printing production software.
They control workflow scheduling or job tracking, using computer database software.
They direct or monitor work of press crews.
They download completed jobs to archive media so that questions can be answered or jobs replicated.
They set up or operate auxiliary equipment, such as cutting, folding, plate-making, drilling, or laminating machines.
They maintain records, such as daily production records, using specified forms.
They monitor machine operations to detect malfunctions or to determine whether adjustments are needed.
They read work orders to determine instructions and specifications for machine set-up.
They set up or operate bindery machines, such as coil binders, thermal or tape binders, plastic comb binders, or specialty binders.
They set up or operate glue machines by filling glue reservoirs, turning switches to activate heating elements, or adjusting glue flow or conveyor speed.
They set up or operate machines that perform binding operations, such as pressing, folding, or trimming.
They stitch or glue endpapers, bindings, backings, or signatures, using sewing machines, glue machines, or glue and brushes.
They trim edges of books to size, using cutting machines, book trimming machines, or hand cutters.
They examine stitched, collated, bound, or unbound product samples for defects, such as imperfect bindings, ink spots, torn pages, loose pages, or loose or uncut threads.
They install or adjust bindery machine devices, such as knives, guides, rollers, rounding forms, creasing rams, or clamps, to accommodate sheets, signatures, or books of specified sizes.
They lubricate, clean, or make minor repairs to machine parts to keep machines in working condition.
They prepare finished books for shipping by wrapping or packing books and stacking boxes on pallets.
They train workers to set up, operate, and use automatic bindery machines.
They apply color to edges of signatures using brushes, pads, or atomizers.
They bind new books, using hand tools such as bone folders, knives, hammers, or brass binding tools.
They compress sewed or glued signatures, using hand presses or smashing machines.
They cut binder boards to specified dimensions, using board shears, hand cutters, or cutting machines.
They cut cover material to specified dimensions, fitting and gluing material to binder boards by hand or machine.
They design original or special bindings for limited editions or other custom binding projects.

They imprint or emboss lettering, designs, or numbers on book covers, using gold, silver, or colored foil, and stamping machines.

They meet with clients, printers, or designers to discuss job requirements or binding plans.
They perform highly skilled hand finishing binding operations, such as grooving or lettering.
They punch holes in and fasten paper sheets, signatures, or other material, using hand or machine punches and staplers.

They receive and mark articles for laundry or dry cleaning with identifying code numbers or names, using hand or machine markers.
They start washers, dry cleaners, driers, or extractors, and turn valves or levers to regulate machine processes and the volume of soap, detergent, water, bleach, starch, and other additives.
They sort and count articles removed from dryers, and fold, wrap, or hang them.
They examine and sort into lots articles to be cleaned, according to color, fabric, dirt content, and cleaning technique required.
They load articles into washers or dry-cleaning machines, or direct other workers to perform loading.
They clean machine filters, and lubricate equipment.
They remove items from washers or dry-cleaning machines, or direct other workers to do so.

They weigh or measure materials, ingredients, or products to ensure conformance to requirements.

They operate or tend machines to mix or blend any of a wide variety of materials, such as spices, dough batter, tobacco, fruit juices, chemicals, livestock feed, food products, color pigments, or explosive ingredients.
They dump or pour specified amounts of materials into machinery or equipment.
They observe production or monitor equipment to ensure safe and efficient operation.
They stop mixing or blending machines when specified product qualities are obtained and open valves and start pumps to transfer mixtures.
They collect samples of materials or products for laboratory testing.
They add or mix chemicals or ingredients for processing, using hand tools or other devices.
They examine materials, ingredients, or products visually or with hands to ensure conformance to established standards.
They record operational or production data on specified forms.
They transfer materials, supplies, or products between work areas, using moving equipment or hand tools.
They tend accessory equipment, such as pumps or conveyors, to move materials or ingredients through production processes.
They read work orders to determine production specifications or information.
They compound or process ingredients or dyes, according to formulas.
They unload mixtures into containers or onto conveyors for further processing.
They clean and maintain equipment, using hand tools.
They mix or blend ingredients by starting machines and mixing for specified times.
They dislodge and clear jammed materials or other items from machinery or equipment, using hand tools.
They open valves to drain slurry from mixers into storage tanks.
They mark or discard items with defects such as spots, stains, scars, snags, chips, scratches, or unacceptable shapes or finishes.
They trim excess material or cut threads off finished products, such as cutting loose ends of plastic off a manufactured toy for a smoother finish.
They cut, shape, and trim materials, such as textiles, food, glass, stone, and metal, using knives, scissors, and other hand tools, portable power tools, or bench-mounted tools.
They separate materials or products according to size, weight, type, condition, color, or shade.
They mark identification numbers, trademarks, grades, marketing data, sizes, or model numbers on products.
They read work orders to determine dimensions, cutting locations, and quantities to cut.
They mark cutting lines around patterns or templates, or follow layout points, using squares, rules, and straightedges, and chalk, pencils, or scribes.
They unroll, lay out, attach, or mount materials or items on cutting tables or machines.
They fold or shape materials before or after cutting them.
They position templates or measure materials to locate specified points of cuts or to obtain maximum yields, using rules, scales, or patterns.
They replace or sharpen dulled cutting tools such as saws.
They count or weigh and bundle items.
They stack cut items and load them on racks or conveyors or onto trucks.
They clean, treat, buff, or polish finished items, using grinders, brushes, chisels, and cleaning solutions and polishing materials.
They route items to provide cutouts for parts, using portable routers, grinders, and hand tools.
They lower table-mounted cutters such as knife blades, cutting wheels, or saws to cut items to specified sizes.
They adjust guides and stops to control depths and widths of cuts.
They transport items to work or storage areas, using carts.
They examine, measure, and weigh materials or products to verify conformance to specifications, using measuring devices, such as rulers, micrometers, or scales.
They set up, operate, or tend machines that cut or slice materials, such as glass, stone, cork, rubber, tobacco, food, paper, or insulating material.
They stack and sort cut material for packaging, further processing, or shipping, according to types and sizes of material.
They review work orders, blueprints, specifications, or job samples to determine components, settings, and adjustments for cutting and slicing machines.
They remove defective or substandard materials from machines, and readjust machine components so that products meet standards.
They press buttons, pull levers, or depress pedals to start and operate cutting and slicing machines.
They adjust machine controls to alter position, alignment, speed, or pressure.
They maintain production records, such as quantities, types, and dimensions of materials produced.
They monitor operation of cutting or slicing machines to detect malfunctions or to determine whether supplies need replenishment.
They start machines to verify setups, and make any necessary adjustments.
They remove completed materials or products from cutting or slicing machines, and stack or store them for additional processing.
They select and install machine components, such as cutting blades, rollers, and templates, according to specifications, using hand tools.

They remove materials or products from molds or from extruding, forming, pressing, or compacting machines, and stack or store them for additional processing.

They thread extruded strips through water tanks and hold-down bars, or attach strands to wires and draw them through tubes.

They pour, scoop, or dump specified ingredients, metal assemblies, or mixtures into sections of machine prior to starting machines.

They couple air and gas lines to machines to maintain plasticity of material and to regulate solidification of final products.

They notify supervisors or other personnel of production problems.

They position products, components, or parts for testing.
They stack or arrange tested products for further processing, shipping, or packaging.

They compare colors, shapes, textures, or grades of products or materials with color charts, templates, or samples to verify conformance to standards.
They adjust, clean, or repair products or processing equipment to correct defects found during inspections.
They fabricate, install, position, or connect components, parts, finished products, or instruments for testing or operational purposes.
They grade, classify, or sort products according to sizes, weights, colors, or other specifications.
They interpret legal requirements, provide safety information, or recommend compliance procedures to contractors, craft workers, engineers, or property owners.
They inspect or test cleantech or green technology parts, products, or installations, such as fuel cells, solar panels, or air quality devices, for conformance to specifications or standards.
They inspect or test raw materials, parts, or products to determine compliance with environmental standards.
They clean, maintain, calibrate, or repair measuring instruments or test equipment, such as dial indicators, fixed gauges, or height gauges.
They check arriving materials to ensure that they match purchase orders, submitting discrepancy reports as necessary.

They monitor machines that automatically measure, sort, or inspect products.

They soften metal to be used in designs by heating it with a gas torch and shape it, using hammers and dies.
They determine appraised values of diamonds and other gemstones based on price guides, market fluctuations, and stone grades and rarity.

They plate articles such as jewelry pieces and watch dials, using silver, gold, nickel, or other metals.
They write or modify design specifications such as the metal contents and weights of items.

They lay out designs on metal stock, and cut along markings to fabricate pieces used to cast metal molds.

They rout out locations where parts are to be joined to items, using routing machines.

They build and shape wax teeth, using small hand instruments and information from observations or dentists' specifications.

They fill chipped or low spots in surfaces of devices, using acrylic resins.
They prepare wax bite blocks and impression trays for use.
They mold wax over denture setups to form the full contours of artificial gums.
They train or supervise other dental technicians or dental laboratory bench workers.
They rebuild or replace linings, wire sections, or missing teeth to repair dentures.
They shape and solder wire and metal frames or bands for dental products, using soldering irons and hand tools.
They fit appliances onto patients, and make any necessary adjustments.
They make orthotic or prosthetic devices, using materials such as thermoplastic and thermosetting materials, metal alloys and leather, and hand or power tools.
They read prescriptions or specifications to determine the type of product or device to be fabricated and the materials and tools required.
They repair, modify, or maintain medical supportive devices, such as artificial limbs, braces, or surgical supports, according to specifications.
They instruct patients in use of prosthetic or orthotic devices.
They take patients' body or limb measurements for use in device construction.
They construct or receive casts or impressions of patients' torsos or limbs for use as cutting and fabrication patterns.

They mix pigments to match patients' skin coloring, according to formulas, and apply mixtures to orthotic or prosthetic devices.
They adjust lenses and frames to correct alignment.
They mount, secure, and align finished lenses in frames or optical assemblies, using precision hand tools.
They mount and secure lens blanks or optical lenses in holding tools or chucks of cutting, polishing, grinding, or coating machines.
They shape lenses appropriately so that they can be inserted into frames.
They assemble eyeglass frames and attach shields, nose pads, and temple pieces, using pliers, screwdrivers, and drills.
They inspect lens blanks to detect flaws, verify smoothness of surface, and ensure thickness of coating on lenses.
They clean finished lenses and eyeglasses, using cloths and solvents.
They select lens blanks, molds, tools, and polishing or grinding wheels, according to production specifications.
They examine prescriptions, work orders, or broken or used eyeglasses to determine specifications for lenses, contact lenses, or other optical elements.
They set dials and start machines to polish lenses or hold lenses against rotating wheels to polish them manually.
They set up machines to polish, bevel, edge, or grind lenses, flats, blanks, or other precision optical elements.
They repair broken parts, using precision hand tools and soldering irons.
They position and adjust cutting tools to specified curvature, dimensions, and depth of cut.
They inspect, weigh, and measure mounted or unmounted lenses after completion to verify alignment and conformance to specifications, using precision instruments.
They remove lenses from molds and separate lenses in containers for further processing or storage.

They inspect and remove defective products and packaging material.

They apply coatings, such as paint, ink, or lacquer, to protect or decorate workpiece surfaces, using spray guns, pens, or brushes.

They load circuit boards, racks or rolls of film, negatives, or printing paper into processing or printing machines.

They maintain records, such as quantities or types of processing completed, materials used, or customer charges.
They measure and mix chemicals to prepare solutions for processing, according to formulas.

They operate scanners or related computer equipment to digitize negatives, photographic prints, or other images.
They operate special equipment to perform tasks such as transferring film to videotape or producing photographic enlargements.
They produce color or black-and-white photographs, negatives, or slides, applying standard photographic reproduction techniques and procedures.

They reprint originals for enlargement or in sections to be pieced together.
They review computer-processed digital images for quality.

They direct safety operations in emergency situations.

They arrange repairs, fuel, and supplies for vessels.
They organize and direct the activities of crew members.
They tow, push, or guide other boats, barges, logs, or rafts.
They clean boats and repair hulls and superstructures, using hand tools, paint, and brushes.
They oversee operation of vessels used for carrying passengers, motor vehicles, or goods across rivers, harbors, lakes, and coastal waters.
They take depth soundings in turning basins.
They perform general labor duties such as repairing booms.
They position booms around docked ships.
They monitor the availability, use, or condition of lifesaving equipment or pollution preventatives to ensure that international regulations are followed.
They monitor engine, machinery, or equipment indicators when vessels are underway, and report abnormalities to appropriate shipboard staff.
They maintain electrical power, heating, ventilation, refrigeration, water, or sewerage systems.

They take numbered tags from customers, locate vehicles, and deliver vehicles, or provide customers with instructions for locating vehicles.

They interact with the public to answer traffic-related questions, respond to complaints or requests, or discuss traffic control ordinances, plans, policies, or procedures.

They recommend replacement, repair, or modification of aircraft equipment.
They recommend changes in rules, policies, standards, and regulations, based on knowledge of operating conditions, aircraft improvements, and other factors.
They approve or deny issuance of certificates of airworthiness.
They investigate air accidents and complaints to determine causes.
They observe flight activities of pilots to assess flying skills and to ensure conformance to flight and safety regulations.

They inspect vehicles or other equipment for evidence of abuse, damage, or mechanical malfunction.
They inspect vehicles or equipment to ensure compliance with rules, standards, or regulations.

They requisition merchandise from supplier, based on available space, merchandise on hand, customer demand, or advertised specials.
They determine proper storage methods, identification, and stock location, based on turnover, environmental factors, and physical capabilities of facilities.
They operate equipment such as forklifts.
They receive, unload, open, unpack, or issue sales floor merchandise.
They monitor meters and pressure gauges to determine consumption rate variations, temperatures, and pressures.
They adjust valves and equipment to obtain specified performance.
They read gas meters, and maintain records of the amounts of gas received and dispensed from holders.
They operate power-driven pumps that transfer liquids, semi-liquids, gases, or powdered materials.
They record instrument readings and operational changes in operating logs.
They move controls and turn valves to start compressor engines, pumps, and auxiliary equipment.
They turn knobs or switches to regulate pressures.
They respond to problems by adjusting control room equipment or instructing other personnel to adjust equipment at problem locations or in other control areas.
They take samples of gases and conduct chemical tests to determine gas quality and sulfur or moisture content, or send samples to laboratories for analysis.
They clean, lubricate, and adjust equipment, and replace filters and gaskets, using hand tools.
They submit daily reports on facility operations.
They connect pipelines between pumps and containers that are being filled or emptied.
They maintain each station by performing general housekeeping duties such as painting, washing, and cleaning.
They monitor gauges and flowmeters and inspect equipment to ensure that tank levels, temperatures, chemical amounts, and pressures are at specified levels, reporting abnormalities as necessary.
They record operating data such as products and quantities pumped, stocks used, gauging results, and operating times.
They communicate with other workers, using signals, radios, or telephones, to start and stop flows of materials or substances.
They tend vessels that store substances such as gases, liquids, slurries, or powdered materials, checking levels of substances by using calibrated rods or by reading mercury gauges and tank charts.
They turn valves and start pumps to start or regulate flows of substances such as gases, liquids, slurries, or powdered materials.
They plan movement of products through lines to processing, storage, and shipping units, using knowledge of interconnections and capacities of pipelines, valve manifolds, pumps, and tankage.
They read operating schedules or instructions or receive verbal orders to determine amounts to be pumped.
They clean, lubricate, and repair pumps and vessels, using hand tools and equipment.
They connect hoses and pipelines to pumps and vessels prior to material transfer, using hand tools.
They test materials and solutions, using testing equipment.
They collect and deliver sample solutions for laboratory analysis.
They tend auxiliary equipment such as water treatment and refrigeration units, and heat exchangers.
They add chemicals and solutions to tanks to ensure that specifications are met.
They pump two or more materials into one tank to blend mixtures.
They monitor control panels during pumping operations to ensure that materials are being pumped at the correct pressure, density, rate, and concentration.
They operate engines and pumps to shut off wells according to production schedules, and to switch flow of oil into storage tanks.
They perform routine maintenance on vehicles and equipment.
They repair gas and oil meters and gauges.
They start compressor engines and divert oil from storage tanks into compressor units and auxiliary equipment to recover natural gas from oil.
They monitor pumps and flow lines for gas and fluid leaks.
They gauge oil and gas production.
They unload and assemble pipes and pumping equipment, using hand tools.
They attach pumps and hoses to wellheads.
They open valves to return compressed gas to bottoms of specified wells to repressurize them and force oil to surface.
They supervise oil pumpers and other workers engaged in producing oil from wells.
They drive trucks to transport high-pressure pumping equipment, and chemicals, fluids, or gases to be pumped into wells.
They prepare trucks and equipment necessary for the type of pumping service required.
They control pumping and blending equipment to acidize, cement, or fracture gas or oil wells and permeable rock formations.
They mix acids, chemicals, or dry cement as required for a specific job.
They change water filters.
They inspect trucks prior to beginning routes to ensure safe operating condition.
They refuel trucks or add other fluids, such as oil or brake fluid.
They fill out defective equipment reports.
They drive trucks, following established routes, through residential streets or alleys or through business or industrial areas.
They operate equipment that compresses collected refuse.
They operate automated or semi-automated hoisting devices that raise refuse bins and dump contents into openings in truck bodies.
They dismount garbage trucks to collect garbage and remount trucks to ride to the next collection point.
They communicate with dispatchers concerning delays, unsafe sites, accidents, equipment breakdowns, or other maintenance problems.
They check road or weather conditions to determine how routes will be affected.
They tag garbage or recycling containers to inform customers of problems, such as excess garbage or inclusion of items that are not permitted.
They clean trucks or compactor bodies after routes have been completed.
They dump refuse or recyclable materials at disposal sites.
They sort items set out for recycling and throw materials into designated truck compartments.
They organize schedules for refuse collection.
They provide quotes for refuse collection contracts.
They make special pickups of recyclable materials, such as food scraps, used oil, discarded computers, or other electronic items.
They verify tank car, barge, or truck load numbers to ensure car placement accuracy based on written or verbal instructions.
They observe positions of cars passing loading spouts, and swing spouts into the correct positions at the appropriate times.
They operate ship loading and unloading equipment, conveyors, hoists, and other specialized material handling equipment such as railroad tank car unloading equipment.
They monitor product movement to and from storage tanks, coordinating activities with other workers to ensure constant product flow.
They record operating data such as products and quantities pumped, gauge readings, and operating times, manually or using computers.
They check conditions and weights of vessels to ensure cleanliness and compliance with loading procedures.
They operate industrial trucks, tractors, loaders, and other equipment to transport materials to and from transportation vehicles and loading docks, and to store and retrieve materials in warehouses.
They seal outlet valves on tank cars, barges, and trucks.
They start pumps and adjust valves or cables to regulate the flow of products to vessels, using knowledge of loading procedures.
They connect ground cables to carry off static electricity when unloading tanker cars.
They test samples for specific gravity, using hydrometers, or send samples to laboratories for testing.
They remove and replace tank car dome caps, or direct other workers in their removal and replacement.
They lower gauge rods into tanks or read meters to verify contents, temperatures, and volumes of liquid loads.
They clean interiors of tank cars or tank trucks, using mechanical spray nozzles.
They operate conveyors and equipment to transfer grain or other materials from transportation vehicles.
They test vessels for leaks, damage, and defects, and repair or replace defective parts as necessary.
They unload cars containing liquids by connecting hoses to outlet plugs and pumping compressed air into cars to force liquids into storage tanks.
They copy and attach load specifications to loaded tanks.
They perform general warehouse activities, such as opening containers and crates, filling warehouse orders, assisting in taking inventory, and weighing and checking materials.
